  "prompt": "What motivates a seafarer to move ashore permanently for a job?",
  "response": "Several factors can motivate a seafarer to transition to a shore-based job:\n\n1. Family considerations\n- Desire to spend more time with family\n- Want to provide more stable home environment\n- Wish to be present for children's upbringing\n\n2. Physical and mental health\n- Demanding maritime work takes a toll on physical health\n- Long periods away from home can cause mental stress\n- Desire for a more predictable lifestyle\n\n3. Career advancement\n- Better career progression opportunities on shore\n- Higher salary potential\n- More diverse job roles and professional development\n\n4. Age and personal circumstances\n- Getting older and seeking less physically demanding work\n- Health limitations\n- Starting a family\n- Wanting more routine and stability\n\n5. Financial reasons\n- Better financial security\n- Regular working hours\n- Consistent income without extended absences\n\n6. Accumulated maritime experience\n- Maritime skills are valuable in shore-based maritime sectors\n- Can transition to roles like marine operations, logistics, maritime consulting\n- Use technical knowledge in different professional capacities\n\n7. Quality of life\n- Less time away from home\n- Regular sleep patterns\n- More consistent social interactions\n- Better work-life balance\n\nEach seafarer's motivation is unique and depends on individual personal and professional circumstances.",
